+<main id="main">
+  <div class="pagewrap">
+    <p class="crumbs" style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:.74rem;letter-spacing:.06em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--ink-soft);margin:0 0 4px;"><a href="../../index.html" style="color:var(--flame)">Home</a> / <a href="../../ch-7/" style="color:var(--flame)">Ch.&nbsp;7</a> / How to Find a Regulation</p>
+    <h1>How to Find a Regulation</h1>
+    <p class="lede">The most reliable route into regulatory research is rarely a cold search of the CFR. This module builds the map: how a rule is made (and the documents each stage leaves for you), the entry routes your question type points to, and the checklist that confirms the text you found is still the law.</p>
+    <div class="howto"><b>How to use this:</b> three short sections — explore the pipeline, choose the entry route for three research questions, then match each currency tool to what it catches. Your work is collected locally for the record you can download at the end. <a href="../reading-regulations/index.html">How to Read a Regulation</a> is the companion: this module finds the text; that one reads it.</div>
+
+    <h2>1 · The rulemaking pipeline — every stage leaves you a document</h2>
+    <p class="secdesc">Click each stage. The shorthand to keep: <b>NPRM = intent · comments = objections · final-rule preamble = the agency's answers.</b></p>
+    <div class="pipe" role="group" aria-label="The four stages of rulemaking">
+      <button class="stage" data-stage="nprm" type="button" aria-expanded="false"><span class="sn">Stage 1 · Federal Register</span><b>Notice of Proposed Rulemaking</b><span class="gives">gives you: original intent</span></button>
+      <button class="stage" data-stage="comment" type="button" aria-expanded="false"><span class="sn">Stage 2</span><b>Public Comment</b><span class="gives">gives you: the objections</span></button>
+      <button class="stage" data-stage="final" type="button" aria-expanded="false"><span class="sn">Stage 3 · Federal Register</span><b>Final Rule</b><span class="gives">gives you: the agency's answers</span></button>
+      <button class="stage" data-stage="cfr" type="button" aria-expanded="false"><span class="sn">Stage 4 · CFR</span><b>Codification</b><span class="gives">gives you: the operative text</span></button>
+    </div>
+    <div class="pipe-explain">
+      <h3 id="pipe-title">Click a stage</h3>
+      <div id="pipe-body" role="status" aria-live="polite"><p>Each stage of rulemaking produces documents a researcher can use. Click through all four.</p></div>
+      <p class="seen" id="pipe-seen">Explored 0 of 4 stages</p>
+    </div>
+
+    <h2>2 · Reading the address — how a CFR citation is organized</h2>
+    <p class="secdesc">The CFR is organized into 50 subject titles. Click each piece of the book's example citation.</p>
+    <div class="citebar">
+      <p class="cite" aria-label="40 C.F.R. section 50.8, shown piece by piece">
+        <button class="citebit" data-bit="title" type="button">40</button>
+        <span>C.F.R.</span>
+        <button class="citebit" data-bit="part" type="button">§&nbsp;50</button>
+        <button class="citebit" data-bit="sec" type="button">.8</button>
+      </p>
+      <p class="citefb" id="citefb" role="status" aria-live="polite">Click a highlighted piece of the citation.</p>
+    </div>
+    <p class="secdesc" style="font-size:.9rem;">Between title and part sits the <b>chapter</b>, which identifies the agency. Two features of every CFR part matter later: the <b>authority note</b> (the statute empowering the agency) and the <b>source note</b> (the Federal Register document that created or last amended the part — the thread you pull to reach the preamble). See them in context in <a href="../reading-regulations/index.html">How to Read a Regulation</a>.</p>
+
+    <h2>3 · Pick the entry route</h2>
+    <p class="secdesc">Your question type points to the door. For each research question, choose the most reliable way in.</p>
+    <div id="routes"></div>
+
+    <h2>4 · The currency checklist — match the tool to what it catches</h2>
+    <p class="secdesc">A regulation you found is not a regulation you can rely on until you confirm it is current. Five tools, five different failure modes. Match them.</p>
+    <p class="scoreline" id="tally2"></p>
+    <div id="currency"></div>
+
+    <div id="export-slot"></div>
+  </div>
+</main>
